            <p:rationale>Maintaining data at multiple sites introduces the risk of inconsistencies, which at best is undesirable. It is inefficient to collect similar data from multiple locations and to decipher potential conflicts manually. By designating a clear data source, administrations can quickly find the correct and most updated information.</p:rationale>
            <p:implications>There is an organization-wide information model in which all important data types have been identified. All data are designated source applications. Applications retrieve data from the source application or receive it via a distribution mechanism. Replicas are never changed, unless there is a controlled synchronization mechanism available. Data are not copied permanently.</p:implications>
